INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'd0f3eb70-34b9-4894-87c5-7b7a87aaf737',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Kubernetes Container Fundamentals — Images, Layers, and Copy-on-Write$escape$,
  $escape$Every Pod in Kubernetes runs containers built from OCI images — ordered stacks of read-only layers produced by each Dockerfile instruction. When the kubelet pulls an image via containerd (the default CRI since Kubernetes 1.24), the runtime unpacks these layers into an overlay filesystem. Each layer is stored once on the node and shared across all containers referencing it — this is why pulling `nginx:1.27` the second time is nearly instant.

When a container starts, the CRI adds a single writable layer on top via OverlayFS (upperdir). Any writes — log files, temp data, config mutations — go there, leaving the shared lower layers untouched. This is copy-on-write (CoW): the file is copied up to the writable layer before modification. On Pod deletion, that writable layer is discarded entirely.

Practical consequence: writing heavily to the container filesystem (not a mounted volume) is slow due to CoW overhead and bloats the ephemeral storage quota tracked per Pod under `resources.limits.ephemeralStorage`. Always mount `emptyDir` or a PVC for write-heavy workloads. Use `kubectl describe node` to inspect image layer caching and eviction pressure on a node.$escape$,
  $escape$# Inspect image layers pulled by containerd on a node
kubectl debug node/my-node-1 -it --image=busybox -- sh

# Inside the debug pod:
crictl images | grep nginx
crictl inspecti nginx@sha256:<digest> | jq '.info.imageSpec.rootfs'

# Check ephemeral storage usage per container
kubectl get pod my-pod -o jsonpath=\
  '{.status.containerStatuses[*].allocatedResources}'

# Set ephemeral storage limit to guard against CoW bloat
# In your Pod spec:
# resources:
#   limits:
#     ephemeral-storage: "512Mi"$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
