INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '94c84155-11e4-4a2f-aaca-b746ad069bf3',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Kubernetes Deployments — Pod Lifecycle, ReplicaSets, and Rolling vs Recreate Strategies$escape$,
  $escape$A Pod is the smallest schedulable unit in Kubernetes — one or more containers sharing a network namespace and lifecycle. Pods are ephemeral: kube-scheduler places them on nodes, but they're never rescheduled if a node dies. That's why you never create bare Pods in production.

A Deployment manages a ReplicaSet, which maintains a stable set of replica Pods. When you update a Deployment's Pod template (e.g. new image tag), the controller creates a new ReplicaSet and orchestrates the transition. The old ReplicaSet is retained — `kubectl rollout undo` exploits this.

Two core strategies control this transition. `RollingUpdate` (default) incrementally replaces Pods using `maxSurge` and `maxUnavailable` — zero-downtime for stateless workloads. `Recreate` terminates all Pods before spawning new ones — useful when your app can't run two versions concurrently (e.g. DB schema migrations with backward-incompatible changes).

Tune `minReadySeconds` and `progressDeadlineSeconds` to control how fast rollouts proceed and when they're marked failed. Use `kubectl rollout status` to block CI pipelines until a Deployment converges.$escape$,
  $escape$apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: api-server
spec:
  replicas: 3
  strategy:
    type: RollingUpdate
    rollingUpdate:
      maxSurge: 1
      maxUnavailable: 0
  minReadySeconds: 10
  progressDeadlineSeconds: 120
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: api-server
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: api-server
    spec:
      containers:
        - name: api
          image: myrepo/api-server:v2.1.0
          readinessProbe:
            httpGet:
              path: /healthz
              port: 8080
            initialDelaySeconds: 5
            periodSeconds: 5$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
