INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '47ce6c26-3677-4057-a6b9-9d9a6d0f0254',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Kubernetes Resource Management — Requests, Limits, and Surviving OOMKill$escape$,
  $escape$Kubernetes schedules pods based on resource requests, not limits. A pod with cpu: 250m and memory: 256Mi requests gets placed on a node that has that capacity available — limits are enforced at runtime by the kernel cgroup. Get this wrong and you'll bleed performance or crash pods.

QoS classes are assigned automatically: Guaranteed (requests == limits for all containers), Burstable (requests < limits), BestEffort (no requests or limits set). Under memory pressure, the kubelet evicts BestEffort first, then Burstable, never Guaranteed.

OOMKill happens when a container exceeds its memory limit — the kernel kills it, not Kubernetes. You'll see OOMKilled in kubectl describe pod under Last State. Root cause: either the limit is too low or there's a memory leak. Use kubectl top pod --containers and Vertical Pod Autoscaler (VPA) in recommendation mode to right-size limits without guessing.

Always set memory requests == limits for critical workloads to lock in Guaranteed QoS. For CPU, limits cause throttling — not kills — so setting cpu limits too low silently degrades latency without any crash signal.$escape$,
  $escape$apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: api-server
spec:
  containers:
  - name: app
    image: myapp:latest
    resources:
      requests:
        memory: "256Mi"
        cpu: "250m"
      limits:
        memory: "256Mi"   # == request → Guaranteed QoS
        cpu: "500m"        # higher than request → allows burst, may throttle$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
