INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '8c1f3cda-2919-4b48-a7be-f2ad44c3e8d3',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Kubernetes Network Policies — Locking Down Pod-to-Pod Traffic$escape$,
  $escape$By default, every pod in a Kubernetes cluster can talk to every other pod — a flat, fully permissive network. Network Policies let you enforce a zero-trust model using label selectors as the access control primitives.

A NetworkPolicy applies to pods matched by `podSelector`. You then define `ingress` and `egress` rules specifying which `namespaceSelector`/`podSelector` combinations are allowed, plus optional port constraints. Policies are additive — multiple policies unioned together.

Critical nuance: NetworkPolicy enforcement requires a CNI plugin that supports it (Calico, Cilium, Weave). Vanilla kubenet ignores them silently.

For ingress controllers (e.g., ingress-nginx), traffic enters from the controller's pod namespace. You must explicitly allow ingress from `namespace: ingress-nginx` or your policy will drop legitimate external traffic post-TLS termination. Use `namespaceSelector` with a label on the ingress namespace rather than hardcoding pod IPs.

Start with a default-deny-all policy per namespace, then whitelist incrementally. This surfaces undocumented service dependencies fast — treat the breakage as a dependency audit.$escape$,
  $escape$apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: NetworkPolicy
metadata:
  name: allow-ingress-controller
  namespace: app
spec:
  podSelector:
    matchLabels:
      app: api
  policyTypes:
    - Ingress
  ingress:
    - from:
        - namespaceSelector:
            matchLabels:
              kubernetes.io/metadata.name: ingress-nginx
      ports:
        - protocol: TCP
          port: 8080$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
