INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'e74c547d-f611-469a-9d4a-cad4fee1323e',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Kubernetes Rolling Updates — Zero-Downtime Deployments and Rollback Strategy$escape$,
  $escape$Kubernetes Deployments use a RollingUpdate strategy by default, replacing Pods incrementally to avoid downtime. Two critical fields control the behavior: `maxUnavailable` (how many Pods can be down simultaneously) and `maxSurge` (how many extra Pods can exist above the desired count). Setting both to 25% on a 4-replica Deployment means Kubernetes kills one old Pod and spins up one new Pod at a time — keeping at least 3 replicas serving traffic throughout.

Readiness probes are non-negotiable here. Without them, Kubernetes promotes a new Pod to the load balancer before your app is actually ready, causing dropped requests. Define a `/healthz` endpoint and configure `readinessProbe` on the container spec.

When a rollout goes wrong, `kubectl rollout undo` reverts to the previous ReplicaSet instantly — no redeployment needed. Kubernetes retains revision history (controlled by `revisionHistoryLimit`). Use `kubectl rollout history deployment/<name>` to inspect revisions and `--to-revision=N` to target a specific one. Pair this with `kubectl rollout status` in your CI pipeline to gate promotions on successful rollouts.$escape$,
  $escape$# Trigger a rolling update
kubectl set image deployment/my-app app=my-app:v2

# Watch rollout progress
kubectl rollout status deployment/my-app

# Inspect revision history
kubectl rollout history deployment/my-app

# Rollback to previous revision
kubectl rollout undo deployment/my-app

# Rollback to a specific revision
kubectl rollout undo deployment/my-app --to-revision=3$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
